# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: the-oxford-magazine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The college entrance is on the north side of High Street, whilst it has a long frontage onto Radcliffe Square.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] To its east is The Queen's College, whilst Hertford College is to the north of All Souls.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The current warden (head of the college) is Sir John Vickers, a graduate of Oriel College, Oxford.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The college was founded by Henry VI of England and Henry Chichele (fellow of New College and Archbishop of Canterbury), in 1438, to commemorate the victims of the Hundred Years' War.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The Statutes provided for a warden and 40 fellows; all to take Holy Orders: 24 to study arts and theology; and 16 to study civil or canon law.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Today the college is primarily a research institution, with no student members.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] All Souls did formerly have students: Robert Hovenden (Warden of the college from 1571 to 1614) introduced undergraduates to provide the fellows with *servientes* (household servants), but this was abandoned by the end of the Commonwealth.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Four Bible Clerks remained on the foundation until 1924.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] For over five hundred years All Souls College admitted only men; women were first allowed to join the college as fellows in 1979, the same year as many other previously all-male colleges in the university.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The American philosopher Susan Hurley became the first female fellow in 1981.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Conservative fellows opposed this change.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Once, upon encountering a woman fellow, the geneticist E.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Ford swung his umbrella at her and shouted "Out of my way, henbird!".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The All Souls College Library (formerly known as the Codrington Library) was founded through a 1710 bequest from Christopher Codrington (1668–1710), a fellow of the college and a wealthy slave and sugar plantation owner.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Codrington was an undergraduate at Oxford and later became colonial governor of the Leeward Islands.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Christopher Codrington was born in Barbados, and amassed a fortune from his sugar plantation in the West Indies.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Under the terms of his will Codrington bequeathed books worth £6,000 to the college in addition to £10,000 in currency for the library to be rebuilt and endowed.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The new library was completed in 1751 to the designs of Nicholas Hawksmoor and has been in continuous use since then.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Today the library comprises some 185,000 items, about a third of which were published before 1800.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The collections are particularly strong in law and history (especially military history).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Sir Christopher Wren was a fellow from 1653.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The design of the sundial, produced in 1658 for the south wall of the Chapel, is attributed to Wren.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The sundial was moved to the quadrangle (above the central entrance to the Library) in 1877.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] In 2020, the College decided to cease referring to the Library as 'The Codrington Library' as part of a set of "steps to address the problematic nature of the Codrington legacy", which comes from wealth derived from slave plantations.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Built between 1438 and 1442, the college chapel remained largely unchanged until the Commonwealth.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Oxford, having been a largely Royalist stronghold, suffered under the Puritans' wrath.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The 42 misericords date from the Chapel's building, and show a resemblance to the misericords at St Mary's Church, Higham Ferrers.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Both may have been carved by Richard Tyllock.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] During the 1660s a screen was installed in the Chapel, which was based on a design by Wren.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] However, this screen needed to be rebuilt by 1713.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] By the mid-19th century the Chapel was in great need of renovation, and so the current structure is heavily influenced by Victorian design ideals.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] There have been a number of rearrangements and repairs of the stained glass windows, but much of the original medieval glass survives.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] All services at the chapel are according to the *Book of Common Prayer*; the *King James Bible* is also used rather than more modern translations.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] All Souls is one of the wealthiest colleges in Oxford with a financial endowment of £486.7 million (2023).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Approximately 95% of its annual income is derived from its endowment as the College does not receive any income from tuition fees.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] While tutors may advise their students to sit for the All Souls examination fellowship, the examination is open to anybody who fulfils the eligibility criteria and the college does not issue invitations to candidates to sit.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Every year in early March, the college hosts an open evening for women, offering women interested in the examination fellowship an opportunity to find out more about the exam process and to meet members of the college.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Each year several dozen candidates typically sit the examination.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Two examination fellows are usually elected each year, although the college has awarded a single place or three places in some years, and on rare occasions made no award.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The competition, offered since 1878 and open to women since 1979, is held over two days in late September, with two papers of three hours each per day.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] It has been described as "the hardest exam in the world".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Two papers (the 'specialist papers') are on a single subject of the candidate's choice; the options are classics, English literature, economics, history, law, philosophy, and politics.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Two papers (the 'general papers') are on general subjects.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] For each general examination, candidates choose three questions from a list.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Before 2010 candidates also faced another examination, a free-form "Essay" on a single, pre-selected word.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Four to six finalists are invited to a viva voce or oral examination.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Previously, these candidates were then invited to dinner with about 75 members of the college.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The dinner did not form part of the assessment, but was intended as a reward for those candidates who had reached the latter stages of the selection process.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] However, the dinner has been discontinued as the college felt candidates worried too often that it was part of the assessment process.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] About a dozen examination fellows are at the college at any one time.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] There are no compulsory teaching or requirements, although examination fellows must pursue a course of study or research at some point within their first two years of fellowship.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] They can study anything for nothing at Oxford with room and board.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] As "Londoners" they can pursue approved non-academic careers if desired, with a reduced stipend, as long as they pursue academia on a part-time basis and attend weekend dinners at the college during their first academic year.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] As of 2011 each examination fellow receives a stipend of £14,842 annually for the first two years; the stipend then varies depending on whether the fellow pursues an academic career.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Until 1979, women were not permitted to put themselves forward for fellowships at All Souls.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] There are also a number of professorial fellows who hold their fellowships by virtue of their University post.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Fellows of the college include the Chichele professors, who hold statutory professorships at the University of Oxford named in honour of Henry Chichele, a founder of the college.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Fellowship of the college has accompanied the award of a Chichele chair since 1870.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Probably the best known former Chichele Professor is Sir Isaiah Berlin.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Perhaps the best known former Professor of the History of War was Cyril Falls.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The Chichele Lectures are a prestigious series of lectures formally established in 1912 and sponsored by All Souls College.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The lectures were initially restricted to foreign history, but have since been expanded to include law, political theory, economic theory, as well as foreign and British history.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] Traditionally the lectures were delivered by a single speaker, but it is now common for several speakers to deliver lectures on a common theme.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] During the hunt the Lord Mallard is preceded by a man bearing a pole to which a mallard is tied – originally a live bird, latterly either dead (1901) or carved from wood (2001).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The last mallard ceremony was in 2001 and the next is due in 2101.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] The precise origin of the custom is not known, but it dates from at least 1632.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] A benign parody of this custom has been portrayed as the Unseen University's "Megapode chase" in Sir Terry Pratchett's 2009 novel *Unseen Academicals*.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/all-souls-college-oxford] In the 2011 historical fantasy novel *A Discovery of Witches* by Deborah Harkness, main character and vampire Matthew Clairmont is a Fellow of All Souls College, having passed the examination in 1989 after writing an essay on the topic of "desire".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The **Ashmolean Museum of Art and Archaeology** (/æʃˈmoʊliən, ˌæʃməˈliːən/) on Beaumont Street in Oxford, England, is Britain's first public museum.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Its first building was erected in 1678–1683 to house the cabinet of curiosities that Elias Ashmole gave to the University of Oxford in 1677.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] It is also the world's second university museum, after the establishment of the Kunstmuseum Basel in 1661 by the University of Basel.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The present building was built between 1841 and 1845.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The museum reopened in 2009 after a major redevelopment, and in November 2011, new galleries focusing on Egypt and Nubia were unveiled.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] In May 2016, the museum redisplayed galleries of 19th-century art.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The museum opened on 24 May 1683, with naturalist Robert Plot as the first keeper.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The building on Broad Street (later known as the Old Ashmolean) is sometimes attributed to Sir Christopher Wren or Thomas Wood.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Elias Ashmole had acquired the collection from the gardeners, travellers, and collectors John Tradescant the Elder and his son, John Tradescant the Younger.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] It included antique coins, books, engravings, geological specimens, and zoological specimens—one of which was the stuffed body of the last dodo ever seen in Europe; but by 1755 the stuffed dodo was so moth-eaten that it was destroyed, except for its head and one claw.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The present building dates from 1841 to 1845.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] It was designed as the University Galleries by Charles Cockerell in a classical style and stands on Beaumont Street.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] One wing of the building is occupied by the Taylor Institution, the modern languages faculty of the university, standing on the corner of Beaumont Street and St Giles' Street.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] This wing of the building was also designed by Charles Cockerell, using the Ionic order of Greek architecture.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Sir Arthur Evans, who was appointed keeper in 1884 and retired in 1908, is largely responsible for the current museum.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Evans found that the keeper and the vice-chancellor (Benjamin Jowett) had managed to lose half of the Ashmole collection and had converted the original building into the Examination Rooms.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Charles Drury Edward Fortnum had offered to donate his personal collection of antiques on condition that the museum was put on a sound footing.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] A donation of £10,000 from Fortnum (£1.12 million as of 2025) enabled Evans to build an extension to the University Galleries and move the Ashmolean collection there in 1894.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] In 1908, the Ashmolean and the University Galleries were combined as the Ashmolean Museum of Art and Archaeology.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The museum became a depository for some of the important archaeological finds from Evans' excavations in Crete.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] After the various specimens had been moved into new museums, the "Old Ashmolean" building was used as office space for the *Oxford English Dictionary*.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Since 1924, the building has been established as the Museum of the History of Science, with exhibitions including the scientific instruments given to Oxford University by Lewis Evans, amongst them the world's largest collection of astrolabes.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Charles Buller Heberden left £1,000 (£42,000 as of 2025) to the university in 1921, which was used for the Coin Room at the museum.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] In 2012, the Ashmolean was awarded a grant of $1.1m by the Andrew W.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Mellon Foundation to establish the University Engagement Programme or UEP.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The programme employs three teaching curators and a programme director to develop the use of the museum's collections in the teaching and research of the university.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The interior of the Ashmolean was extensively modernised during the early 21st century and now includes a restaurant and large gift shop.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] In 2000, the Chinese Picture Gallery, designed by van Heyningen and Haward Architects, opened at the entrance of the Ashmolean and is partly integrated into the structure.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] It was inserted into a lightwell in the Grade I listed building and was designed to support future construction from its roof.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Apart from the original Cockerell spaces, this gallery was the only part of the museum retained in the rebuilding.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The gallery houses the Ashmolean's own collection and is also used from time to time for the display of loan exhibitions and works by contemporary Chinese artists.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] It is the only museum gallery in Britain devoted to Chinese paintings.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The Bodleian Art, Archaeology and Ancient World Library (formerly the Sackler Library), incorporating the older library collections of the Ashmolean, opened in 2001 and has allowed an expansion of the book collection, which concentrates on classical civilisation, archaeology, and art history.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Between 2006 and 2009, the museum was expanded to the designs of architect Rick Mather and the exhibition design company Metaphor, supported by the Heritage Lottery Fund.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The $98.2 million rebuilding resulted in five floors instead of three, with a doubling of the display space, as well as new conservation studios and an education centre.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The renovated museum re-opened on 7 November 2009.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] On 26 November 2011, the Ashmolean opened to the public the new galleries of Ancient Egypt and Nubia.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] This second phase of major redevelopment now allows the museum to exhibit objects that have been in storage for decades, more than doubling the number of coffins and mummies on display.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The project received lead support from Lord Sainsbury's Linbury Trust, along with the Selz Foundation, Mr.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Christian Levett, as well as other trusts, foundations, and individuals.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Rick Mather Architects led the redesign and display of the four previous Egypt galleries and the extension to the restored Ruskin Gallery, previously occupied by the museum shop.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] In May 2016, the museum opened new galleries dedicated to the display of its collection of Victorian art.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The main museum contains huge collections of archaeological specimens and fine art.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] It has one of the best collections of Pre-Raphaelite paintings, majolica pottery, and English silver.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The archaeology department includes the bequest of Arthur Evans and so has a collection of Greek and Minoan pottery.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The department also has an extensive collection of antiquities from Ancient Egypt and the Sudan, and the museum hosts the Griffith Institute for the advancement of Egyptology.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] In 2013 a museum was opened in the 17th-century "Tudor House" at Broadway, Worcestershire, in the Cotswolds, in partnership with the Ashmolean Museum.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] In 2017 the museum became known as the Broadway Museum and Art Gallery.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The collection includes paintings and furniture from the founding collections of the Ashmolean Museum, given by Elias Ashmole to the University of Oxford in 1683, and local exhibits expand upon elements of the timeline of the village.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] On 31 December 1999, during the fireworks that accompanied the celebration of the millennium, thieves used scaffolding on an adjoining building to climb onto the roof of the museum and stole Cézanne's landscape painting *View of Auvers-sur-Oise*.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] Valued at £3 million, the painting has been described as an important work illustrating the transition from early to mature Cézanne painting.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] As the thieves ignored other works in the same room, and the stolen Cézanne has not been offered for sale, it is speculated that this was a case of an artwork stolen to order.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] The Cézanne has not been recovered and is one of the FBI's Top Ten Art Crimes.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/ashmolean-museum] In 2010 several of the Egypt Exploration Society's Oxyrhynchus Papyri held by the museum were allegedly stolen from the collection and sold to the American *Museum of the Bible*.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The **Association for the Education of Women** or **Association for Promoting the Higher Education of Women in Oxford** (**AEW**) was formed in 1878 to promote the education of women at the University of Oxford.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] It provided lectures and tutorials for students at the four women's halls in Oxford, as well as for female students living at home or in lodgings and was dissolved in 1920 when women were admitted as members of the university.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] in 1873 a Lectures for Women Committee was set up by a group of Oxford women, including the "don's wives" Louise Creighton, Charlotte Byron Green, Bertha Johnson, Lavinia Talbot and Mary Ward who were later involved in the AEW.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The lectures started in 1874 and were given by university academics such as Arthur Johnson, William Stubbs and Henry Nettleship.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The association was formed at a meeting at Jesus College in 1878 and G G Bradley, the Master of University College, Oxford was chosen as the first chairman.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] It was realised that a new hall in Oxford was required where women students could live whilst at university.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The consensus was split on religious grounds: some wanted a hall which ignored a woman's denomination, whilst others like Lavinia Talbot supported a hall for Anglo Catholics.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The first women's halls at the university, the Anglican Lady Margaret Hall and the denomination free Somerville Hall, opened in 1879.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] Two further women's halls were St Hugh's Hall, founded by Elizabeth Wordsworth in 1886, and St Hilda's Hall, founded by Dorothea Beale in 1893.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] A number of non-resident students also enrolled in 1879 and were supervised by the Lady Secretary of the AEW until a principal was appointed in 1893.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The AEW was their parent organisation until 1910.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The term *Home-Students* was used from 1891 and *Society of Oxford Home-Students* from 1898.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The society received a royal charter as St Anne's College in 1952.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The AEW organised lectures and tutorials for female students at all the women's halls.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] At first lectures were held in rooms above a baker’s shop in Little Clarendon Street and later in a former Baptist Chapel in Alfred Street (now Pusey Street).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] From 1880 women students began to be admitted to lectures at the men's colleges.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The halls were originally intended to be hostels, leaving teaching to the AEW.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] However they gradually started to employ their own tutors, starting at Somerville with Lilla Haigh in 1882 and at LMH with Eleanor Lodge in 1895.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] A dispute with Somerville over the appointment of tutors led to the resignation of Bertha Johnson as Lady Secretary of the AEW in 1894.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] In 1910 the University set up a Delegacy for Women Students, for the first time officially recognising their existence and allowing them to take university exams.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The delegacy took over the registration of women students and their entry for examinations from the AEW, as well as the supervision of the Society of Oxford Home-Students.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] In 1895 Henry Nettleship's widow Matilda donated his library to the AEW where it formed a shared collection for all women students, based in the attics of the Clarendon Building.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] It later became the library of the Society of Oxford Home-Students.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] In 1920 women were allowed to become members of the university and receive degrees.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The first matriculation ceremony was on 7 October 1920 and the first degrees were awarded on 14 October 1920.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The AEW was wound up in 1920, followed in 1921 by the Delegacy for Women Students.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/association-for-the-education-of-women] The women honorary secretaries of the AEW were: Charlotte Byron Green (1880–1883), Bertha Johnson (1883–1894) and Annie Rogers (1894–1920).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] With a governing body of a master and around 80 fellows, the college's main buildings are located on Broad Street with additional buildings to the east in Jowett Walk and Holywell Manor.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] As one of the larger colleges of Oxford University, Balliol typically has around 400 of both undergraduates and graduates.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The college pioneered the PPE degree in the 1920s.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol has notable alumni from a wide range of disciplines.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] These include 13 Nobel Prize winners and 4 British prime ministers.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol College was founded in about 1263 by John I de Balliol under the guidance of Walter of Kirkham, the Bishop of Durham.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] According to legend, the founder had abducted the bishop as part of a land dispute and as a penance he was publicly beaten by the bishop and had to support a group of scholars at Oxford.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] After de Balliol's death in 1268, his widow, Dervorguilla of Galloway (their son would go on to become King of Scotland), made arrangements to ensure the permanence of the college in that she provided capital and in 1282 formulated the college statutes, documents that survive to the present.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol lays claim to being the oldest Oxford college, though this is disputed by both University College and Merton.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] However, Balliol also acknowledges that the other two have legitimate claims on their respective bases, depending on what criteria are used to define the oldest.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] For more than 700 years, Balliol College admitted men only.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] New College had in 1964 resolved to admit women, but had been prevented from doing so without the approval of the university, which averred that this would be detrimental to the existing women's colleges.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] On 2 June 1971, a consilium at Balliol voted 26–2 to admit women and at the subsequent college meeting on 6 December 1971 it was resolved 30–8 to admit women "as soon as the change in its Statutes permitting this was approved by the Privy Council".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Permission was granted by the university on 8 March 1977.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] With the appointment of Carol Clark to a Tutorial Fellowship in Modern Languages in 1973, Balliol became the first ancient all-male college to appoint a female fellow.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Before the full admission of women as undergraduates, the college had decided to establish a co-educational graduate institution.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The decision was made on 16 March 1964 and the senior tutor approached St Anne's College shortly after this.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The creation of the Balliol–St Anne's Graduate Institution with St Anne's in 1967 led to the coeducation of men and women on the Holywell Manor site.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Following the arrival of women at Balliol and men at St Anne's in 1979, the joint Graduate Institution was terminated in 1984 by the consent of both colleges.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Holywell Manor is now solely a part of Balliol College.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In 1979, along with many other previously all-male colleges, Balliol accepted its first cohort of female students.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] One of the first woman undergraduates to live at Balliol was Elena Ceva-Valla, who arrived on 16 September 1979.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Other female undergraduates who arrived that term were Cressida Dick, Katy Koralek and Penny Phillips.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In 2010, the college unveiled a sundial in the Garden Quad commemorating the thirtieth anniversary of the admission of women to the college, inscribed with the phrase "About Time".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The first portrait of a woman in hall since that of the co-founder, Dervorguilla of Galloway, was unveiled in 2012, depicting benefactor and Oxford Internet Institute founder Dame Stephanie Shirley.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This portrait has since been joined by portraits of Carol Clark and the mathematician Dame Frances Kirwan.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In 2018, Dame Helen Ghosh succeeded Sir Drummond Bone to become the college's first female master.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In the same year, Dame Frances Kirwan became the twentieth Savilian Professor of Geometry and the first woman to hold that post.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In 2021, students sent an open letter to the college and protested regarding their welfare following an alleged incident of sexual assault on a female graduate student that was covered by Al Jazeera English.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol has a more or less permanent teaching staff, known as fellows.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The college statutes provide for various categories of fellows and these include both tutorial fellows and professorial fellows.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Professorial fellows are professors and readers of the university who are allocated to the college by the university.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] One of these professorships is the Beit Professor of Commonwealth History, which is currently held by James Belich.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The Professorship of Internet Studies is currently held by political scientist Philip N.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Other professorships include the Boden Professor of Sanskrit and the Montague Burton Professor of International Relations.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Official fellows are those who hold tutorial or administrative appointments in the college.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] There are also senior and junior research fellows.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The college can also elect "distinguished persons" to honorary fellowships.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The fellows are supplemented by academics on short-term contracts.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In addition, there are visiting international academics who come to Oxford for periods of up to a year, an example of this is the George Eastman Visiting Professorial Fellowship.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol College is run by the master and fellows of the college.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The master of the college must be "the person who is, in their [the Fellows] judgement, most fit for the government of the College as a place of religion, learning, and education".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The current master is Dame Helen Ghosh, former Director-General of the National Trust and Home Office Permanent Secretary, and an alumna of St Hugh's and Hertford colleges.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Although the rules in no way suggest there is a preference for an alumnus or fellow of the college to be chosen, there have been few who were not.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Only one in the twentieth century had no previous connection.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] A former student of the college, Baruch Blumberg, was the first American master and the first Nobel Laureate, receiving his prize in medicine for the identification of the hepatitis B virus.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The former Master of Balliol, Sir Drummond Bone, was a post-graduate student (Snell Exhibitioner from Glasgow University) and a scholar of the Romantic poet Lord Byron, and held the post from October 2011 to April 2018.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The college has been on its present site since its inception by Balliol's scholars as their residence with 1263 considered the traditional "foundation" date.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The oldest parts of the college are the north and west ranges of the front quadrangle, dated to 1431, respectively the medieval hall, west side, now the "new library" and the "old library" first floor north side.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The ground floor is the Old Senior Common Room.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol's second library pre-dates the publication of printed books in Europe.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] There is a possibility that the original Master's Chamber, south west side, adorned with a fine oriel window, is earlier than these; it is now the Master's Dining Room.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] William Grey, Bishop of Ely, was a benefactor of the college in the 15th century.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Grey devoted much care to the collection of manuscripts, and wherever he lived constantly employed scribes to make copies of books he could not otherwise obtain.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Many of these he had adorned with costly miniatures and initial letters by the skill of an artist who worked for him at Florence.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] It was his desire to make his collection the nucleus of a library for Balliol College, to the building of which, as well as to that of the master's lodgings and of the old buttery and hall, he contributed largely.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The work was finished about 1477 by Robert Abdy, then master of the college, and enriched with some two hundred manuscripts, the bishop's gift.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Of these, many were destroyed in the reign of Edward VI and during the great rebellion, and by Wood's time few of the miniatures in the remaining volumes had escaped mutilation.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] But by 1890, no less than 152 of Grey's codices were still in the possession of the college, and form a large part of Roger Mynors's 1963 catalogue of the college's manuscripts.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The bishop's coat of arms (gules, a lion rampant, within a bordure engrailed argent) is displayed on two windows of the Old Library, and in the panels below the window of the Master's dining room.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The chapel is the third (perhaps fourth) on the site and was designed by William Butterfield in 1857.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Alfred Waterhouse designed the main Broad Street frontage of the college (1867–68), along with gateway and tower, known as the Brackenbury Buildings after philanthropist and donor Hannah Brackenbury, replacing earlier structures (Staircases I–VII).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The first staircase next to the chapel contains the organ scholar's lodgings.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Under a statute of 1881, New Inn Hall, one of the remaining medieval halls, was merged into Balliol College in 1887.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol acquired New Inn Hall's admissions and other records for 1831–1887 as well as the library of New Inn Hall, which largely contained 18th-century law books.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The New Inn Hall site was later sold and is now part of St Peter's College, Oxford.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] South-side is the front part of the Master's Lodgings on Broad Street from the Waterhouse improvements of the 1860s of the front quad.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This building incorporates the original Master's chamber, seen in the old quadrangle, which is now the Master's dining room.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The neighbour to this is the Fisher Building of 1759 (Stc X) The undistinguished looking Stc XI, south west side, is in fact the oldest structure in this quadrangle, 1720, originally intended as accommodation for scholars from Bristol, hence its name.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Continuing the west-side Stc XII–XIV dates from 1826, by George Basevi, and marks the beginnings of the college's academic renaissance being required for the increasing number of commoners applying for places.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Stc XV by Warren of 1912 filled in the last gap of the quadrangle; the ground floor and basement is the principal Junior Common Room.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This obscures the lines of the Salvin designed Stc XVI–XIX with the tower of 1853, as does the 1968 building by Beard Stc XX, replacing a Victorian structure.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This completely hides a formal gateway similar to that at the Broad Street main entrance, this can be viewed outside from Little Magdalen Street, through the gap marked XIX is the small function room "Massey Room".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] At the north side of Stc XX is the "Back Gate" which is part of the 1906 Warren building, west and north side, Stc XXI.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] 1 St Giles' is its neighbour which is part of the college and houses the Oxford Internet Institute.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Beard's Stc XXII replaces Victorian rooms, which were provided from the Vivian Bulkeley-Johnson benefaction.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Beard's Stc XX and XXII are connected by the Snell Bridge accommodation at third-floor level, which was provided from Glasgow University's Snell Benefaction.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The college's dining hall was built in 1877, replacing an older hall in the front quadrangle, which had become too small for the college's population.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The land w for this was purchased by and donated to the college by its then Master, Benjamin Jowett.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Designed by Alfred Waterhouse, the hall is built in geometric style, using Bath stone and Tisbury stone, with roof and woodwork made of oak.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The hall features a Willis organ, also instituted by Jowett to allow the hall's use for secular music concerts.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The old hall became part of the library.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The ground floor contains the college bar and shop, known as "The Buttery" (west side) and the Senior Common Room lunch room (east side).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The 1966 new Senior Common Room range (Stc XXIII) (northern and eastern sides) was a benefaction of the Bernard Sunley Foundation and contains some smaller rooms and the principal SCR lounge, replacing Victorian facilities.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Below this is a Lecture Room ("LR XXIII").
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The east side of the quad is a neighbouring wall with Trinity College, at the southern end is the Master's Garden, in front of the chapel, and the Fellows' Garden in front of the "Old" (Senior) Common Room.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The Tower forming the corner between the "Old Hall" and "Old Library" is also by Salvin, of 1853 and balances that at Stc XVI–XIX.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] These are now disused, following the construction of the university Physical and Theoretical Chemistry Laboratory on South Parks Road.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The majority of research and post-graduate students are housed in the Holywell Manor complex, a Grade II listed building acquired by Balliol in 1932 under the direction of Kenneth Norman Bell.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] It hosts a collection of artworks by alumni of the college, including a mural by Gilbert Spencer depicting the college's founding, and hosts a biennial Holywell Manor Festival, Garden Party, and Garden Play.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The Manor from 1967 until the full admission of women at Balliol in 1979 was host to the Balliol-St Anne's Graduate Institution, including students from St Anne's College, Oxford.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Former residents include Bill Clinton and Masako, Empress of Japan.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The 20th century saw several further additions to the college's accommodation, the Martin Building of 1966 ('Holywell *Minor*, a reference to Holywell Manor, across the road) and the Dellal Building (1986) for graduates on Manor Road.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Jowett Walk has also provided accommodation for some non-Balliol undergraduates, as part of an arrangement with Wadham College, Oxford.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] From 2010, St Cross Church, next to the Manor, has been the college's Historic Collections Centre, an extension to the library's services.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The church dates from the 11th or 12th century and is a Grade I listed building.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This is the third time an Oxford college has incorporated a redundant church as a Library (see Lincoln College and St.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In 2017, the college entered into a specialised financial arrangement which enabled it to project a new 200 plus 'study-bedsits' accommodation range at the Master's Field/ Jowett Walk/ St Cross Road site which would also replace the Eastman Professor's House, Martin and Dellal buildings there.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This would mean a net increase of approximately 140 rooms fulfilling the college's long-term intention of providing accommodation to all its undergraduates for all their degree terms and also some rooms for dons.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The project includes ten new buildings and a new sports pavilion, including a space for dining, events, spectators and squash courts in the basement.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The first building opened in spring 2019 and the completion and occupation of the rest is due by January 2021.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In the first phase, work began on the south of the site, at the corner of Jowett Walk and St Cross Road, to provide the accommodation for undergraduates and the new pavilion.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol College, and its previous Master Andrew Graham, played a major role in 2000–01 in setting up the Oxford Internet Institute.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This was the first multidisciplinary research and policy centre in a European university devoted to examining the impact of the Internet on society.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] It is a department within the Social Sciences Division of Oxford University, but is physically located within the grounds of Balliol, and its previous Director (William H.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Dutton) was a Professorial Fellow of Balliol.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Each year the college matriculates approximately 260 undergraduates and postgraduates combined according to the most recent data which is from the three-year period 2021–2023.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The same source gives the socio-demographic profile of the students is as follows: male 54.5%; state educated 69.6%; white 73.4%.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The proportion of male students decreased from 60.6% between the years of 2015 and 2017.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The college provides its students with facilities including accommodation, the Hall (refectory), a library, two bars, and separate common rooms for the fellows, the graduates and undergraduates.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The JCR provides many services from laundry facilities, one of the few entirely student-run bars left in Oxford (the Manager, Lord/Lady Lindsay, is elected each year by students in the JCR) to a student-run cafeteria known as Pantry.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] There is a garden quadrangle and a nearby sports ground (the Master's Field) and boathouse.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The sports ground is mainly used for cricket, tennis, hockey and football.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Croquet may be played in the Master's Field or, in the summer term, in the garden quadrangle.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The majority of undergraduates are housed within the main college or in the modern annexes (Jowett Walk buildings) around the sports ground.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The graduates are housed mainly within Holywell Manor which has its own bar, gardens, common room, gym and computing facilities.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Along with many of the ancient colleges, Balliol has evolved its own traditions and customs over the centuries, many of which occupy a regular calendar slot.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The patron saint of the college is Saint Catherine of Alexandria.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] On her feast day (25 November), a formal dinner is held for all final year students within Balliol.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This festival was well established by 1550.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Another important feast is the Snell Dinner.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This dinner is held in memory of John Snell, whose benefaction established exhibitions for students from the University of Glasgow to study at Balliol (the first exhibitioners were matriculated in 1699) one of whom was Adam Smith.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The feast is attended by fellows of Balliol College, the current Snell Exhibitioners, and representatives from Glasgow University and St John's College, Cambridge.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The MCR has one black-tie dinner each term: the Christmas Dinner in Michaelmas, Burns Night in Hilary, and the May Dinner in Trinity Term.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] By far the most eccentric event is The Nepotists carol-singing event organised by the college's Arnold and Brackenbury Society.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This event happens on the last Friday of Michaelmas term each year.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] On this occasion, Balliol students congregate in the college hall to enjoy mulled wine and the singing of carols.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The evening historically ended with a rendition of "The Gordouli" (see Balliol–Trinity rivalry below) on Broad Street, outside the gates of Trinity College, although in recent years the song has been sung from within the college walls.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] A college society which no longer survives is the Hysteron Proteron Club, which aimed to live one day of each term backwards.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol also takes pride in its college tortoises.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The original tortoise, who lived at the college for at least 43 years, was known as Rosa, named after the Marxist Rosa Luxemburg.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Each June, pet tortoises from various Oxford colleges are brought to Corpus Christi College where they participate in a very slow race; Balliol's own Rosa competed and won many times.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Rosa disappeared in the Spring of 2004, and while numerous conspiracy theories abounded, none is officially recognised by the college.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] However, on 29 April 2007, Chris Skidmore, a graduate of Christ Church working at the House of Commons, donated a pair of tortoises - one to his own college, and one to Balliol, where he had attended an open day in 1999.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The new tortoise, Matilda, died in April 2009.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Taking care of the resident tortoise is one of the many tasks assigned to Balliol students each year.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This position, known as "Comrade Tortoise", has been filled by a first year student.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] For many years, there has been a traditional and fierce rivalry shown between the students of Balliol and those of its immediate neighbour to the east, Trinity College.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] It has manifested itself on the sports field and the river; in the form of songs (of varying degrees of offensiveness) sung over the dividing walls; and in the form of "raids" on the other college.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The rivalry reflects that which also exists between Trinity College, Cambridge and Balliol's sister college, St John's College, Cambridge.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In college folklore, the rivalry goes back to the late 17th century, when Ralph Bathurst, President of Trinity, was supposedly observed throwing stones at Balliol's windows.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In fact, in its modern form, the rivalry appears to date from the late 1890s, when the chant or song known as a "Gordouli" began to be sung from the Balliol side.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The shouting of chants over the wall is still known as "a Gordouli", and the tradition continues as the students gather to sing following boat club dinners and other events.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The traditional Gordouli is said to have been sung by Balliol and Trinity men in the trenches of Mesopotamia in the First World War.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol became known for its radicalism and political activism in the 20th century, and saw an abortive coup in the 1960s in which students took over the college and declared it "the People's Republic of Balliol".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The contrast between the radical tendencies of many Balliol students and the traditional conservatism and social exclusivity of Trinity gave the rivalry an extra edge.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The fact that Balliol (in contrast to Trinity) had admitted a number of Indian and Asiatic students also gave many of the taunts from the Trinity side a distinctly racist tone: Balliol students, for example, were sometime referred to as "Basutos".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In *Five Red Herrings* (1931), a Lord Peter Wimsey novel by Somerville alumna Dorothy L.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Sayers, Lord Peter (a Balliol man) is asked whether he remembers a certain contemporary from Trinity.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] "'I never knew any Trinity men,' said Wimsey.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] One of the wittier raids from Balliol, in 1962 or 1963, involved the turfing of the whole of Trinity JCR (complete with daffodils).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The last incident suspected to relate to the feud was the vandalism of Trinity's Senior Common Room pond, which led to the death of all but one of the fish.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In 1880, seven mischievous Balliol undergraduates published *The Masque of B-ll--l*, a broadsheet of forty quatrains making light of their superiors – the master and selected fellows, scholars, and commoners – and themselves.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The outraged authorities immediately suppressed the collection, and only a few copies survived, three of which found their way into the college library over the years, and one into the Bodleian Library.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Verses of this form are now known as Balliol rhymes.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The best known of these rhymes is the one on Benjamin Jowett.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This has been widely quoted and reprinted in virtually every book about Jowett and about Balliol ever since.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] This and 18 others are attributed to Henry Charles Beeching.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The other quatrains are much less well known.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] William Tuckwell included 18 of these quatrains in his *Reminiscences* in 1900, but they all came out only in 1939, thanks to Walter George Hiscock, an Oxford librarian, who issued them personally then and in a second edition in 1955.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] A wide range of figures who have contributed deeply to public life were either educated or taught at Balliol.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol people were, for example, prominent in establishing the International Baccalaureate, the National Trust, the Workers Educational Association, the welfare state, the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament and Amnesty International.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Five former Balliol students and seven fellows became Nobel Laureates, with Linus Pauling winning two Nobel Prizes.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Evolutionary biologist Richard Dawkins was a Balliol student from 1959 to 1962.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol has produced four British prime ministers; H.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Asquith, Harold Macmillan, Edward Heath and Boris Johnson.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Royal alumni include; Empress Masako of Japan, Ja'afar of Negeri Sembilan of Malaysia, Olav V of Norway and his son Harald V of Norway, current King of Norway.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] In terms of critics, Balliol has produced A.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Other notable contemporary philosophers include J.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Hare, Michael Sandel, Joseph Raz, Peter Geach, Michael Otsuka, Michael E.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Balliol has also contributed to the sporting world; Iftikhar Ali Khan Pataudi and his son Mansoor Ali Khan Pataudi, both India cricket captains and the 8th and 9th Nawabs of Pataudi respectively, were both Balliol graduates who played for the university.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] US Olympian rower Caryn Davies received her MBA at Balliol.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] The last two being opposed in their election by Edward Heath and Lord Bingham of Cornhill respectively.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/balliol-college-oxford] Members of the college have been elected to masterships not only at Balliol but also at other colleges and include the former master of Christ's College, Cambridge, Jane Stapleton, a former fellow of Balliol.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/begbroke-science-park] The site has been the home of research facilities since 1960, when the Weed Research Organisation was established there.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/begbroke-science-park] It was later used as the Technology Centre of the Cookson Group.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/begbroke-science-park] The university owns 200 acres (81 ha) of land surrounding the research park, mainly devoted to agriculture, of which the Science Park is developed on a 10-acre site at the centre.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/begbroke-science-park] In 2017, a new science enterprise centre, known as the Begbroke Innovation Accelerator, was opened in the park as an extension of the Centre for Innovation and Enterprise.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] Bernard O'Donoghue was born on 14 December 1945 in Cullen, County Cork, Ireland, where he lived on a farm. “My father was a terrible and reluctant farmer, though my mother was very good, she got stuck into it,” he recalled in an interview with Shevaun Wilder.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] When he was 16, his father died suddenly, and the family left Ireland, moving to Manchester, England.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] He attended St Bede's College, a Catholic school near Alexandra Park, from where he moved on to Lincoln College, Oxford in 1965 to read English literature.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] After a year working as a computer programmer with IBM, O’Donoghue returned to Oxford to do a post-graduate degree in Medieval studies, also at Lincoln College.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] He has remained in Oxford ever since, apart from an annual return to County Cork, “It's good to have two places,” he says, “Two perspectives.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] When you're in one, you think you belong to the other one." He obtained a lectureship in English at Magdalen College, Oxford, remaining with the college from 1971 to 1995.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] O’Donoghue moved to Wadham College, Oxford in 1995 as Fellow and tutor in medieval English literature and English language.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] He specialised in Chaucer studies, but also taught Modern Irish Literature, especially poetry.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] His former students include the actress Rosamund Pike, the journalist and satirist Ian Hislop, and the writers Alan Hollinghurst and Mick Imlah.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] O’Donoghue retired from teaching in 2011, but stayed with Wadham as an emeritus fellow.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] In 2019 he took over the editorship of the *Wadham Gazette* from his colleague, Geoffrey Brooker, the successor of the Wadham classicist James Morwood.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] Bernard O'Donoghue’s first poetry collection was *Razorblades and Pencils*, published by John Fuller as “a beautiful green pamphlet" in 1982.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] Fuller, O'Donoghue’s colleague at Magdalen College, Oxford, was an English poet and novelist, who ran the college poetry society, the Florio Society of which O’Donoghue was a member.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] Fuller also ran a publishing operation “on an ancient, oily machine in his garage”, The Sycamore Press, which, in addition to O’Donoghue, also published more established poets such as W.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] This was followed by *Poaching Rights*, published in Ireland by Peter Fallon, "a marvellous, alert editor", at Gallery Press in 1987, then a second pamphlet, *The Absent Signifier* in 1990, published by another English poet, Peter Scupham, at his Mandeville Press in 1990.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] O'Donoghue's next collection, *The Weakness*, was published by Chatto & Windus in 1992.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] O'Donaghue himself regarded this as his most significant work from the Magdalen years.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] The painting O’Donoghue chose for the cover of *Here Nor There* is *St Nicholas Rebuking the Tempest* by Bicci di Lorenzo (ca.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] This was one of three Chatto covers featuring a work of Medieval art, a nod to the inspiration found by the author in the Medieval, and earlier Anglo-Saxon elegies such as *The Seafarer* and *The Wanderer*, "which he has loved since he first encountered them as part of his primary degree programme.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] They are, he says, 'his model for the perfectly-formed short poem'".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] Death recurs throughout O’Donoghue’s poetry, notably in *Outliving*, his last book for Chatto & Windus (2003) This collection starts with *The Day I Outlived My Father* with its bleak opening lines: *Yet no one sent me flowers, or even/ asked me out for a drink*.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] This poem features regularly in poetry readings by the author, along with *The Iron Age Boat at Caumatruish*, *In Millstreet Hospital* and *Shells of Galice*.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] The Anglo-Saxon motif returns in O’Donoghue’s next book, *Farmer's Cross* (Faber & Faber 2011).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] "One of the collection's highlights is O'Donoghue's masterly translation of the Old English lyric *The Wanderer*".
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] Both this, and the next collection, *The Seasons of Cullen Church* (Faber & Faber 2016), were shortlisted for the T.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] The Irish poet Brendan Kennelly once said that “O'Donoghue's poetic world is one where stories are more important than ideas.” O’Donoghue agreed: "He's right.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] O’Donoghue has contributed to the discourse on modern poetry with two studies of Seamus Heaney.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] The first was *Seamus Heaney and the Language of Poetry* (1995), "a pioneering study of Heaney", followed in 2008 by *The Cambridge Companion to Seamus Heaney*.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] Day-Lewis: The Golden Bridle*, (co-Edited with Albert Gelpi, Oxford University Press, 2017) attempts to restore the reputation of “one of the major figures in twentieth-century English poetry by any objective measure” by presenting a selection of his prose writings.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] Two early medieval anthologies by O'Donoghue were *The Courtly Love Tradition* (Manchester University Press, 1982) and the related *Thomas Hoccleve Selected Poems* (Fyfield Books, 1982).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] He moved on from the medieval to the Irish with *Oxford Irish Quotations* (Oxford University Press, 1999).
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] This included over two thousand quotations such as "The old literature of Ireland...has been the chief illumination of my imagination all my life." from W.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] O'Donoghue received the 1995 Whitbread prize for Poetry for his collection *Gunpowder*, and the Cholmondeley Award in 2009.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] He has also been shortlisted multiple times for the T.S.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature in 1999.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/bernard-o-donoghue] He succeeded Seamus Heaney as Honorary President of the Irish Literary Society of London in 2014.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/big-data-institute] The **Big Data Institute** (**BDI**), part of the Li Ka Shing Centre for Health Information and Discovery, is an interdisciplinary research institute at the University of Oxford.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/big-data-institute] The institute brings together researchers from both the Nuffield Department of Population Health and the Nuffield Department of Medicine.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/big-data-institute] The BDI building is on the Old Road Campus in Headington, east Oxford, England.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/big-data-institute] Academics from the BDI are advising the British government about a mobile phone app to track the COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] It now functions "as a commentator on university affairs", that is, an independent forum where members of Congregation can debate academic policy.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] While it is distributed along with the *Oxford University Gazette*, it sometimes carries articles critical of the University's leadership.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] The magazine continues to publish poetry, including the work of Oxford Professor of Poetry Simon Armitage.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] As of 2025, the current literary editor is the poet Jane Griffiths, who took up this position after Lucy Newlyn.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] Newlyn had been the literary editor of the magazine since 2011.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] The previous literary editor of the magazine was the poet Bernard O'Donoghue, who was preceded by the poet David Constantine.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] The general editor of the magazine in 2021 was Tim Horder, Emeritus Fellow in Medicine at Jesus College, Oxford.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] Latterly issued four times each term, the magazine became online only in December 2020 saving the university £45,000 a year.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] In 2022 the university ended all personnel and computer support, leaving the editors unable to continue publication.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] Academic staff prepared a motion for debate at Congregation in November 2022 which "instructs" the university council to reverse the decision and to ensure the continued publication of *Oxford Magazine* under the preexisting arrangements.
[src:the-oxford-magazine/the-oxford-magazine] It should not be confused with *Oxford Magazine* or *In Oxford Magazine*, both commercial listings/shopping magazines covering the City of Oxford, nor with an earlier periodical also called *The Oxford Magazine* which was published in London from 1768 to 1776.
